#####################50##########################
:dpi
DPI (Dots Per Inch):

Changes the resolution of the page that is 
displayed.

The options for resolution are common for 
several screens and printers.  

If you have a 100 dpi monitor and select 100 
dpi, the page should appear actual size.
 
If you select 300 dpi, the page will appear
3 times larger than actual size.

:orient
Orientation:

Controls which way the page is oriented on
the screen.

This is useful for rotating and viewing slides, 
which are often rendered in "landscape" as 
opposed to "portrait" orientation.

#####################50##########################
:pagesize
Size:

Controls the size of the page in virtual space 
(not on the screen--unless the dpi of the page 
matches the screen exactly).

USLetter	8.5 x 11 inches
USLegal		8.5 x 14 inches

A3 (European)	29.7 x 42.0 cm
		11.693 x 16.535 inches

A4 (European)	21.0 X 29.7 cm
		8.268 x 11.693 inches

A5 (European)	14.8 x 21.0 cm
		5.827 x 8268 inches

B5 (European)	17.6 x 25.0 cm
		6.929 x 9.842 inches

#####################50##########################
:aa
AntiAlias:

Enables the AntiAliasing feature in the X11/NeWS
server for the pages of this document.

This feature allows for viewing of documents at
a size and apparent resolution that is closer
to that of a printer.

:timeout
Job Timeout (sec):
 
Sets the timeout for the current job to the
value entered.
 
If a PostScript page cannot be interpreted and
displayed in the given time, a blank page will
be displayed and a job time-out error will be
written into the Output Log window.

 
:method
Ignore PostScript Structuring Comments:
 
Changes the way PageView determines the number
of pages in a document.

Normally, PageView checks a file for PostScript
structuring comments, such as a "%%Page:" to
denote the start of a new page.

However, some documents do not conform to
these conventions. When you choose Ignore
PostScript Structuring Comments, an alternate
method of determining page breaks is used.
 
This alternate method may increase the time it
takes for PageView to determine the number of
pages in a document. You may want to turn this
option on only when the normal method of 
determining page breaks doesn't work.

